lynx analysis script

2025-05-20

Research Question: Do agreement levels with statements about lynx reintroduction differ between sample groups Farmers, Public, and Scientists even after controlling for demographics?

Load required packages

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(betareg)
library(emmeans)
library(corrplot)
library(car)

Loading and Cleaning the data

Public data

# Load public data
publicdata <- read.csv("Lynx Survey - Public sample_22 April 2025_14.51.csv")

# Clean the data (removing the first two rows and renaming columns)
publicdata_labelsremoved <- publicdata[-c(1, 2), ]

#rename columns
publicdata_renamedfull <- publicdata_labelsremoved %>%
  rename(
    gender = X5.1,
    age = X5.2,
    education = X5.4,
    urbanrural = X5.5
  )

#colnames(publicdata_renamedfull) #check
#nrow(publicdata_renamedfull)

#table(publicdata_renamedfull$gender)
# Remove non-binary or 'Prefer not to say' gender responses
publicdata_renamed <- publicdata_renamedfull %>%
  filter(!gender %in% c("Non-binary or other", "Prefer not to say"))
#table(publicdata_renamed$gender)

#table(publicdata_renamed$education)

# Exclude "Primary School" responses
publicdata_renamed <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  filter(education != "Primary School")
#table(publicdata_renamed$education)
#

# After renaming the columns, recode the urbanrural variable to combine urban and rural
publicdata_renamed <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  mutate(
    urbanrural = case_when(
      urbanrural %in% c("Quite urban", "Very urban (eg, a city or large town)") ~ "Urban",  # Combine the two "urban" categories
      urbanrural %in% c("Quite rural", "Very rural (eg, a small village or the countryside)") ~ "Rural",  # Combine the two "rural" categories
      TRUE ~ urbanrural  # Keep other values as they are (if any)
    )
  )


# Exclude rows where the attention check (AC) is Agree
#nrow(publicdata_renamed) #n=297
publicdata_renamed <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  filter(AC != "Agree")
#nrow(publicdata_renamed)#n=297

# Convert the Duration..in.seconds column to numeric, coercing non-numeric values to NA
publicdata_renamed$`Duration..in.seconds.` <- as.numeric(publicdata_renamed$`Duration..in.seconds.`)

# Check if there are still any NA values in the Duration..in.seconds. column
#sum(is.na(publicdata_renamed$`Duration..in.seconds.`))


# Calculate mean and median for public data
public_duration_stats <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  summarise(
    mean_duration = mean(`Duration..in.seconds.`, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_duration = median(`Duration..in.seconds.`, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# Print the stats for public data
#print(public_duration_stats)  #median 380

#class(publicdata_renamed$`Duration..in.seconds.`)#check

# Calculate the threshold, which is half the median duration
thresholdpublic <- 380 / 2

# Filter the data for participants who answered in less than half of the median time
fast_respondents_public <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  filter(`Duration..in.seconds.` < thresholdpublic)

# Count how many participants answered in less than half the median time
#nrow(fast_respondents_public) #7

# Remove fast respondents from the public data
publicdata_renamed <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  filter(`Duration..in.seconds.` >= thresholdpublic)

# Verify the number of rows after removal
#nrow(publicdata_renamed)  # This will give the updated number of responses
#290 

# Add a column to identify group
publicdata_renamed$Group <- "Public"


#adding participant ID
publicdata_renamed <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  mutate(Participant_ID = paste0("public_", row_number()))


# Reshape to long format
public_long <- publicdata_renamed %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("X3."),
    names_to = "Statement",
    values_to = "Agreement"
  ) %>%
  select(Participant_ID, everything()) %>%
  mutate(
    Statement = gsub("_1", "", Statement),
    Agreement = as.numeric(Agreement),
    Statement = gsub("X3\\.", "", Statement),
    Statement = factor(Statement, levels = as.character(1:18))
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Agreement) & Agreement != "")

Visualising the raw data

mean agrement per statement for all groups

# Ensure Agreement is numeric
combined_data$Agreement <- as.numeric(combined_data$Agreement)


# Calculate mean agreement per statement
statement_agreement <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(Statement) %>%
  summarise(mean_agreement = mean(Agreement, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

# Add descriptive labels for each statement
statement_labels <- data.frame(
  Statement = as.character(1:18),
  Label = c(
    "1. risk to sheep", "2. farming sector", "3. farmer stress",
    "4. deer reduction", "5. nature recovery", "6. climate change",
    "7. majority decision", "8. inclusive consultation", "9. fairness for farmers",
    "10. compensation fairness", "11. compensation rejected",
    "12. morally right", "13. willingness", "14. food production",
    "15. coexistence abroad", "16. harm vs good",
    "17. tourism", "18. excitement"
  )
)

# Add theme data
statement_theme_mapping <- data.frame(
  Statement = as.character(1:18),
  Theme = c(
    rep("Agriculture and Livestock", 3),
    rep("Ecology and Climate", 3),
    rep("Social Challenges", 5),
    rep("Mindset and Morals", 5),
    rep("Recreation and Tourism", 2)
  )
)
# Merge labels into the data
statement_agreement <- left_join(statement_agreement, statement_labels, by = "Statement")
statement_agreement <- left_join(statement_agreement, statement_theme_mapping, by = "Statement")

# Order labels by statement number
statement_agreement$Label <- factor(statement_agreement$Label, levels = statement_labels$Label)

# Order labels by ascending agreement
statement_agreement <- statement_agreement %>%
  arrange(mean_agreement) %>%
  mutate(Label = factor(Label, levels = Label))


# Plot with descriptive labels
ggplot(statement_agreement, aes(x = Label, y = mean_agreement, fill = Theme)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 100), breaks = seq(0, 100, 10)) +
  labs(
    title = "Mean Agreement Score per Statement",
    x = "Statement",
    y = "Mean Agreement (0 = Strongly Disagree, 100 = Strongly Agree)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

plotting boxplots by theme - all in one plot

# Custom professional theme
custom_theme <- theme_minimal(base_size = 13) +
  theme(
    strip.text = element_text(size = 13, face = "bold"),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 11),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 11),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 13, face = "bold"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 11),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 15, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey85"),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = NA)
  )

# Consistent colors for groups
group_colors <- c("Farmer" = "#8DA0CB", "Public" = "#66C2A5", "Scientist" = "#FC8D62")



# Ensure Statement is character for joining
combined_data$Statement <- as.character(combined_data$Statement)

# Join Theme info BEFORE mutating it
combined_data <- left_join(combined_data, statement_theme_mapping, by = "Statement")
combined_data<- left_join(combined_data, statement_labels, by = "Statement") 



# Create the boxplot with adjusted spacing between facets and y-axis title distance
full_boxplots <- ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = Label, y = Agreement, fill = Group)) +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.6, alpha = 0.9, outlier.shape = NA, 
               position = position_dodge2(padding = 0.3)) +  # more space between groups
  scale_fill_manual(values = group_colors) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 100), expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.05))) +
  facet_wrap(~ Theme, scales = "free_x", ncol = 2) +  # Adjust ncol to 3 to fit top row with 3 columns
  labs(
    title = "Agreement with Lynx Reintroduction Statements by Group and Theme",
    x = NULL,
    y = "Agreement Score (0 = Strongly Disagree, 100 = Strongly Agree)",
    fill = "Group"
  ) +
  custom_theme +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 13),
    panel.spacing = unit(0.8, "lines"),  # adjust space between facets (both horizontal and vertical)
    axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(r = 15))  # increase distance between y-axis title and plot
  )

# Print the plot
print(full_boxplots)

# Save the plot
ggsave("lynx_agreement_facet_plot.png", plot = full_boxplots, 
       width = 13, height = 13, dpi = 300)

plotting boxplots by theme - separate plots

# Fix the order of Statement levels numerically
combined_data$Statement <- factor(combined_data$Statement, levels = as.character(1:18))
unique_themes <- unique(combined_data$Theme)

for (t in unique_themes) {
  theme_data <- combined_data %>% 
    filter(Theme == t) %>%
    mutate(Statement = factor(Statement, levels = as.character(sort(as.numeric(unique(Statement))))))
  
  p <- ggplot(theme_data, aes(x = Statement, y = Agreement, fill = Group)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    theme_minimal() +
    labs(
      title = paste("Agreement by Statement and Group  Theme:", t),
      x = "Statement",
      y = "Agreement Score (0100)"
    ) +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    ylim(0, 100)+ 
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2")
  
  
  print(p)
}

Beta Regression analysis

Rescale agreement for beta regression

combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(
    Agreement_scaled = (Agreement * 0.99 + 0.5) / 100,
    # avoid 0 and 1
    age = as.numeric(age),
    gender = factor(trimws(gender)),
    education = factor(trimws(education)),
    urbanrural = factor(trimws(urbanrural)),
    Group = factor(Group)  
  )

Beta regression excluding Farmers

##### Create a new dataset excluding Farmers
combined_data_nofarmer <- combined_data %>%
  filter(Group != "Farmer")


# Create a list of unique statements (same as before)
statements_nofarmer <- unique(combined_data_nofarmer$Statement)

# Create a list to store models without farmers
models_nofarmer <- list()

cat("========== BETA REGRESSION (NO FARMERS) ==========\n\n")
## ========== BETA REGRESSION (NO FARMERS) ==========
# Loop through statements and fit beta regression with covariates
for (s in statements_nofarmer) {
  data_subset <- combined_data_nofarmer %>%
    filter(Statement == s)
  
  # Fit beta regression model with covariates
  model <- betareg(
    Agreement_scaled ~ Group + age + gender + education + urbanrural,
    data = data_subset
  )
  
  # Save model in list
  models_nofarmer[[s]] <- model
  
  
  # Print model summary
  cat("=== Statement", s, "===\n")
  print(summary(model))
  cat("\n\n")
}

# Extract p-value for Group effect (Public vs Scientist)
summary_model <- summary(model)
group_row <- which(rownames(summary_model$coefficients) == "GroupScientist")
p_val <- if (length(group_row) > 0) summary_model$coefficients[group_row, "Pr(>|z|)"] else NA

estimate marginal means

plot average agreement with significance stars from beta regression

#Add theme mapping
statement_theme_mapping <- data.frame(
  Statement = as.character(1:18),
  Theme = c(
    rep("Agriculture and Livestock", 3),   # 13
    rep("Ecology and Climate", 3),         # 46
    rep("Social Challenges", 5),           # 711
    rep("Mindset and Morals", 5),          # 1216 
    rep("Recreation and Tourism", 2)       # 1718
  )
)

# Add descriptive labels for each statement
statement_labels <- data.frame(
  Statement = as.character(1:18),
  Label = c(
    "1. risk to sheep", "2. farming sector", "3. farmer stress",
    "4. deer reduction", "5. nature recovery", "6. climate change",
    "7. majority decision", "8. inclusive consultation", "9. fairness for farmers",
    "10. compensation fairness", "11. compensation rejected",
    "12. morally right", "13. willingness", "14.food production",
    "15.coexistance abroad", "16.harm vs good",
    "17.tourism", "18.excitement"
  )
)

#prepare data frames
plot_data <- data.frame()
emm_summary <- data.frame()
contrast_summary <- data.frame()


for (s in names(models_nofarmer)) {
  model <- models_nofarmer[[s]]
  model_data <- model$model
  
  
# Get the estimated marginal means per group
  emm <- tryCatch({
    ref_grid <- ref_grid(model, data = model_data)
    emmeans(ref_grid, ~ Group, type = "response")
  }, error = function(e) {
    message(paste("Skipping Statement", s, "due to error:", e$message))
    return(NULL)
  })
  
  if (is.null(emm)) next
  

  # Perform pairwise comparison between Public and Scientist
  contrast_df <- as.data.frame(contrast(emm, method = "pairwise"))
  
  # Extract p-value for the Public vs Scientist contrast
  p_val <- contrast_df$p.value[contrast_df$contrast == "Public - Scientist"]
  
  # Create a data frame for merging results
  means_df <- as.data.frame(emm)
  
  # Add results to summary tables
  means_df$Statement <- s
  contrast_df$Statement <- s
  
  emm_summary <- rbind(emm_summary, means_df)
  contrast_summary <- rbind(contrast_summary, contrast_df)
  
  
  merged_df <- means_df %>%
    mutate(
      Statement = s,
      p_value = ifelse(Group == "Public", p_val, NA)  # Only assign p-value to "Public"
    )
  
  # Remove duplicate rows to keep one per group per statement
  merged_df <- merged_df[!duplicated(merged_df[, c("Statement", "Group")]), ]
  
  plot_data <- rbind(plot_data, merged_df)
  
  
  
  # Add progress message
  cat(" Processed Statement:", s, "\n")
}

# Modify the label assignment to exclude the star for 6.climate change, this is to comply with significance levels from beta regresssion
plot_data$label <- ifelse(
  !is.na(plot_data$p_value) & plot_data$p_value < 0.05 & plot_data$Statement != "6", 
  "*", 
  ""
)


# Split the data by Theme
theme_list <- split(plot_data, plot_data$Theme)


##### Create a plot for each theme
theme_plots <- lapply(names(theme_list), function(theme_name) {
  data <- theme_list[[theme_name]] %>%
    mutate(Label = factor(Label, levels = statement_labels$Label[match(as.character(1:18), statement_labels$Statement)]))
  
  
  ggplot(data, aes(x = Group, y = emmean, fill = Group)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge(width = 0.9)) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = asymp.LCL, ymax = asymp.UCL), 
                  width = 0.2, position = position_dodge(width = 0.9)) +
    geom_text(data = subset(data, Group == "Public"), 
              aes(label = label), 
              x = 1.5, y = 1, inherit.aes = FALSE, size = 10) +
    facet_wrap(~ Label, scales = "fixed", nrow = 1) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
    labs(
      title = paste("Estimated Agreement by Group:", theme_name),
      subtitle =  "* indicates p < 0.05 for group effect (Public vs Scientist)",
      x = "Group",
      y = "Estimated Agreement (scaled 01)",
      fill = "Group"
    ) +
    scale_x_discrete(labels = NULL) +
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
    ylim(0, 1)
})

# Name and print plots
names(theme_plots) <- names(theme_list)
for (theme_name in names(theme_plots)) {
  print(theme_plots[[theme_name]])
  
  # Save each plot as a PNG file
  ggsave(
    filename = paste0("emm_plot_", gsub(" ", "_", theme_name), ".png"),
    plot = theme_plots[[theme_name]],
    width = 10, height = 6, dpi = 300
  )
  
}
